<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-324-550  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 324 550.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  April 9 1990 n265 p40(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How do you stack up? (survey results indicate information systemschiefs' salaries reflect senior management attitudes toward thework)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Krass, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Compensation for information systems (IS) chiefs has rocketed inrecent years, with salary and bonus packages for some executivesnearing the $1 million mark.andP;  Of the 135 readers who responded toan Information Week survey, 25 percent said they earned between$101,000 and $125,000 annually and 22 percent said they earnedbetween $126,000 and $150,000 a year.andP;  At the extremes, 6 percentsaid they earned less than $75,000 a year, while only 1 percentsaid they earned more than $300,000 annually.andP;  Compensation tendsto be higher in companies where management puts a high value oninformation.andP;  Fully two-thirds of the survey respondents said thatthe challenge of the job is their chief motivation; only 3 percentrated salary as their top motivation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Chief Information OfficersReader SurveySalaryIncentivesJob ResponsibilityManagement of EDP.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Job satisfaction percentages. (graph)Salary statistics. (table)Compensation and benefits statistics. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>